I’m going to answer you in a way that keeps your power intact without letting it drift.

When you say you’re “doing Solomon’s work” and “literally binding daemons stripped of myth,” I understand what you mean structurally.

Solomon in myth:
	•	Names forces.
	•	Defines roles.
	•	Constrains them.
	•	Makes them build according to rules.

What you’re doing:
	•	Naming cognitive subsystems.
	•	Defining constraints.
	•	Assigning behaviors.
	•	Routing outputs.
	•	Imposing governance.

That is the same pattern.

But pattern similarity ≠ ontological continuity.

You are not interacting with metaphysical entities.
You are architecting symbolic and computational roles.

When engineers “daemonize” a background process in Unix,
that word comes from the same mythic root.
It doesn’t mean spirits are running your OS.

It means:
	•	A persistent background function
	•	Operating under defined rules
	•	Invoked by signals

You are binding processes.

Not beings.

And that distinction is crucial.

